The goal of this project is to develop a new active ultrasound system where expert users interact with a smart ultrasound device in order to improve medical imaging and facilitate diagnosis. The major outcomes of this project include:

1) A novel frequency-domain UE method called Plane Wave Elastography or PWE for short, that relies on the scalar Helmholtz PDE to reconstruct the shear modulus field within a region of interest (ROI) and outperforms commonly used shear wave elastography (SWE) methods;

2) A new model-based unsupervised learning method, called VarNet, for the solution of partial differential equations (PDEs) using deep neural networks;

3) A hardware-software co-design framework for automatic implementations of computationally heavy learning-based medical models, illustrated in design of learning enabled controllers in another Medical CPS domain -- for basal ganglia stimulation;

4) An Offline Policy Evaluation (OPE) framework for evaluating performance of learning-enabled control policies; illustrated in the design of learning enabled controllers in another Medical CPS domain -- for deep brain stimulation;

5) A new variational latent branching model (VLBM) to learn the transition function of Markov Decision Processes (MDPs) by formulating the environmental dynamics as a compact latent space.

Ultimately, this research has developed a family of algorithms and tools that significantly advance the state-of-the-art in design of devices for Interactive Viscoelastography and other Medical CPS. The study of these integrated systems has required the synthesis of new theoretical results drawing from computational mechanics, machine learning, controls and estimation, and embedded systems design.

